<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ArtifactDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-L8_t7vb2eAWcaU7jKTOb9A" name="uam_technical_locations_model,_kxoK0M6nEdymj4NXv8-FYA" guid="-L8_t7vb2eAWcaU7jKTOb9A" authors="DW Enstrom" changeDate="2015-02-12T14:51:16.507-0500" changeDescription="New" version="2.0.0">
  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Technical Locations Viewpoint is used, within the enterprise architecture context, to either specify technical&#xD;
    patterns for the enterprise, or if the scope, scale and resources are appropriate to document a physical&#xD;
    (near-implementation) level view of enterprise locations. Both may be described, if desired and appropriate, as well.&#xD;
    UAM processes and templates support either or both of these approaches and objectives.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Technical_Perspective__Technical_Locations_Model&quot;&#xD;
name=&quot;XE_Technical_Perspective__Technical_Locations_Model&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The locations viewpoint&amp;nbsp;is a key element of the Technical Perspective. It may be used to show how entities (data),&#xD;
    processes and the network aspects (and the required supporting infrastructure) are organized and deployed throughout&#xD;
    the system (or enterprise). In other words, some entity model, process model and roles model aspects may be shown to&#xD;
    best advantage in the locations model. Partitioning and layering is used to separate these aspects in the locations&#xD;
    model.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The locations model works best if layering is used to deal with complexity and to provide views appropriate for the&#xD;
    audience and objectives; and comprehension is greatly improved. Detail is hidden, while allowing for its definition in&#xD;
    lower layers, as required in meeting the objectives of the architecture effort.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
  <purpose>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Technical Locations Model is model of the structure of locations, each of which contain servers, roles&amp;nbsp;and&#xD;
    processes) that when structured into a model define the set of&amp;nbsp;technical locations.&amp;nbsp; It defines the&#xD;
    locations, and the contents and services at these locations,&amp;nbsp;where the system operates.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
  <representationOptions>&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>UML Representation&lt;/strong>: Package stereotyped as «TPL_TLM» containing deployment diagrams.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A &lt;strong>Technical&lt;/strong> &lt;strong>Locations Model&lt;/strong> may have the following properties:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;b>Introduction:&lt;/b> A textual description that serves as a brief introduction to the model.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;b>Packages:&lt;/b> The packages in the model, representing a hierarchy&amp;nbsp;(contained within the Technical&#xD;
        Perspective package).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;b>Nodes:&lt;/b> The nodes in the model, owned by the packages stereotyped as «TPL_Location», «TPL_Domain»,&#xD;
        «TPL_Zone», «TPL_Server», etc.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;b>Relationships:&lt;/b> The relationships in the model, owned by the packages stereotyped as «TPL_Comms».&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;b>Diagrams:&lt;/b> The diagrams in the model, owned by the packages.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A Technical Locations Model is created to illustrate the conceptual location at which the &quot;system&quot; has a&#xD;
    presence.&amp;nbsp;This artifact is enclosed within the Technical Perspective artifact.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Technical Locations Model is a way of expressing the business conducted at and between locations where it operates.&#xD;
    Locations are now Technical, but may include logical &quot;locations&quot; based upon security concepts, see: &lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/whitepapers/uam_security_reference_model_3EA07B63.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_KGs_oMX8EdyDYN2-y9-AqA&quot;>Whitepaper: A Reference Model for Enterprise Security&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;(i.e., Domains and&#xD;
    Zones). The types of locations and interactions between them are what are modeled. The business activities supported or&#xD;
    provided at each location are also described.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Decide on the following:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The sub-package structure for the Technical Location Model package: function-based structure or coherence/coupling&#xD;
        based;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Properties to include;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Whether or not any extensions to the Unified Modeling Language (UML) are needed; additional stereotypes or&#xD;
        profile&amp;nbsp;for example;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The level of formality&amp;nbsp;and detail in the model (see&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
        href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_technical_pers_C469D0B5.html&quot; guid=&quot;_5qRZYAbnEeSyDIZvZjuaLg&quot;>Guideline:&#xD;
        Technical Perspective&lt;/a>);&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Whether a single model or multiple models will be used.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p class=&quot;BodyTable&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 6pt 0in&quot;>&#xD;
    The modeling elements are too extensive to include, see: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/supportingmaterials/uam_tpl_simple_FA24A330.html&quot; guid=&quot;_w5B_8EWJEeOfR_FtRm9PUg&quot;>Supporting&#xD;
    Material: TPL Summary&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></representationOptions>
